  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and involves international cooperation to combat financial crimes. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in the 1920s during Prohibition era in the United States\n- Initially associated with organized crime and disguising proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Initial Legislation:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States was one of the first comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions and maintain records\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances\n- Established international frameworks for combating drug-related money laundering\n- Encouraged countries to criminalize money laundering as a distinct offense\n\n4. FATF Establishment:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) created in 1989\n- Developed international standards and recommendations for AML regulations\n- Promoted global cooperation in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n5. Significant Expansion:\n- Post-9/11 regulations significantly expanded money laundering prohibitions\n- Patriot Act (2001) enhanced reporting requirements and penalties\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n\n6. Ongoing Evolution:\n- Continuous updates to address emerging financial technologies\n- Growing emphasis on cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations",
